How travel prices have evolved since 1989
Until 1989 there were only 5 state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Cedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autotourist.
Travel agencies at that time offered travels especially in the countries of the Socialist Block, as travels to the West were very limited.
Czech tourists traveled for vacation in East Germany, Soviet Union (Sotchi, Crimea and the Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (the two in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A great exception for the period from 1962 to 1972 when he was allowed to travel to Yugoslavia and the regime began to have an inclination to the west and travel to Yugoslavia was very limited for Czech tourists.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that it was not permitted for citizens of the socialist block (also for the Czechoslovakia) to travel individually even within the framework of the socialist countries.
If the Czechoslovakia citizen wanted to travel individually, for example, to Poland or to the Soviet Union, he needed an invitation letter otherwise the individual journey was not permitted.
Travel agencies at that time also offered travels to the West, however, it was necessary to make the queue all night with a sleeping bag or to have a "good knowledge" within the travel agency.
And even after that, it was not yet won.
The agreement for currencies that was the condition of travelling to the west was denied to "politically incorrect" people who could not travel at all.
However, the Czechoslovakia currency was not exchangeable and it was not possible to obtain financial resources without the currency agreement (Western currency) to travel to the West.
The Czechs were most often spending their holidays in the country where there were many houses and chalets that the Czechs had purchased and this habit lasted until now.
The Czech travel has been a huge revolution since 1989.
Although until 1989 the holidays in East Germany and Bulgaria were the maximum, the Czechs spent last year 4 million holiday days abroad in countries around the world.
The great paradox we do not know today is that the most popular country is Croatia where it was not possible to go freely until 1989 as part of Yugoslavia of that time.
The removal of visa in the 1990s in the neighbouring countries of the West has caused a huge short-term wave of visits, especially in Austria to Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovakia could not travel for a long time by plane to the west that everyone wanted to see at least a moment.
For example, in Paris travel organizations made the Czechs sleep in tents in parks because our income did not allow us to pay the hotel or pension.
The typical feature of a Czech journey was at this time to gain with itself its own preserved food, sausage, etc.... to save.
Another important moment was also the interchangeability of the Czech crown that finally allowed our tourists to be able to buy freely from the Western currency after decades.
Our level of life as well as the average wage increased that caused around 1997 another important moment.
Thanks to a growing demand for travel, travel agencies have started preparing tours with air charter connections since 1997, which through contracts significantly reduced costs compared to the previous ones.
At the end of the late 90s, Czechs had a visa-free connection with almost most developed countries around the world except the EU who later facilitated our trips.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolution tourism, when the first air charter was prepared to an exotic country, Thailand, from the Czech Republic.
Since this year and every year, direct air charters take Czech tourists to the far away hot countries; this winter there will be 12 exotic destinations from the Czech Republic.
More than 100000 Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
Another interesting moment in this period that symbolizes our post-revolutionary development came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the EU removed the Czech tourist visa and allowed our country to remain fully in the group of developed countries.
In 2008, the Czechs also spent more than half of their holiday abroad (50, 3%) for the first time in history, and for the first time in history, more than 15,000 crowns per person spent on holidays abroad including annexed charges.
