The Mexican Institute of Social Security (IMSS) announced that it conducted an investigation to discover the gen of obesity in children and young people, called the protocol ‘Genetics of obesity for children and adolescents’, which will allow the markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, Miguel Cruz López, head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry of the Hospital of Specialities of the 20th century Medical Center, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social assistants had been formed.
This team is supported by specialists and graduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Centre for Advanced Research and Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
The research invites the people who are entitled to participate in the sports units of the IMSS in Valle de México, where proofs for minors are performed every Saturday from 8:00 p.m.
He stressed that the protocol began at the Cuauhtémoc Sportive Unit (Estado de México Poniente) and that from October 8, the activity takes place at the Sportive Unit of Nezahualcóyolt (Estado de México Oriente).
After reaching the goal of gathering 500 or 600 minors, the study will continue at the Sportive Unit Independencia (South of the Federal District) and finally at the Sportive Unit Morelos (North of the Federal District).
He explained that the objective of this research and its knowledge of the components and importance of genetics regarding the development of obesity and the identification of risk factors in children and young Mexicans to prevent the emergence of chronic degenerative diseases.
As will be celebrated on 14 November on the World Diabetes Day, he noted that the goal is to gather three thousand children and young people between six and 14 years of age, with the consent and supervision of their parents, for the application of specific nutritional questionnaires.
They will also be asked about their physical activity and their family heritage history of their diseases, in order to avoid risk factors that cause diseases such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He explained that on Saturday, all participants of the anthropometric measurements (weight, size, circumference of size), blood pressure, determination of glucose levels, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin and genetics (seeing to identify people associated with infant obesity).
Cruz López reported that this investigation is the result of healthcare professionals’ concern about the alarming weight gain in minors.
"Health surveys in 1999 and 2006 reported that in just six years, in the case of boys, a 77 per cent increase in obesity and in the case of girls of 47 per cent; overweight, a dramatic increase was also observed," the IMSS specialist said.
He stated that the justification for the search for markers is based on the fact that the population of the country is different from the other from its genetic history.
On average, Mexicans have 65 percent of Indo-American inheritance, 30 percent European and 5 percent African, and this condition is reflected in people associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity resulted in the inability to burn the excess energy consumed (calories), which deposes itself in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for participants is the complete assessment of children, allowing them to detect whether they have a degree of overweight or obesity.
It even said that the presence of dark color plaques (acanthosis) on the neck and the front-bras indicates the likelihood of suffering from metabolic and even pre-diabetes alterations.
The information is managed confidentially, doctors give it in writing to parents, to which each is explained the measures and changes in lifestyle they have to make to prevent diseases.
Cruz López explained that there are three major components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic disorders: sedentaryism, which is the lack of daily physical activity, stay most of the day sitting in front of the TV and using means of transport instead of walking on short distances.
Another cause is the high caloric intake, i.e. the highest consumption of sugar beverages, carbohydrates (tames - meat to corn milk wrapped in leaves of corn -, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with high fat and protein content and genetics analyzed in this protocol.
UNAM's asphalt will avoid cassettes
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the UNAM Chemistry Faculty, develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with better efficiency, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the signals were resolved, it would no longer be necessary to repair about 200 thousand cassis each rain season in the Metropolitan Zone of Mexico, warned Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher at the UNAM Chemistry Faculty (FQ), who fully assured that if the construction and maintenance of the pavement would be appropriate, even if the bitumineus were reduced.
A technological opinion on cassis, organized as part of the International Year of Chemistry, announced that the laboratory responsible for developing modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with similar characteristics asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera estimates that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely warm, like some of the northern cities of the country, to improve efficiency, and therefore, the formation of cassettes.
He explained that the asphalt, the heaviest part of the oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, molecules with a more heavier molecular weight, called asphaltene, and molecules with a low molecular weight, called malthene, which together give the pavement its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of the asphalt consists in the fact that at high temperatures of nearly 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees C its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees C it has a nearly solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes crushed.
This means that in the streets the resistance of asphalt is not uniform and changes during the day depending on environmental and temperature conditions, the chemical engineering specialist warns.
The FQ researcher observed that the streets of Ciudad de México in the majority were covered by a flexible pavement, consisting of six layers of materials, of which the last three involve asphalt.
Among the more superficial layers is the asphalt layer, formed by small asphalt bathstones and later compacted.
Each of the small stones that form the layer, he reported, is bathed with asphalt.
When vehicles pass there by generating efforts, this allows the forces to spread very well into the pavement.
If we had modified asphalt, they would spread better, according to the chemical engineer.
On the asphalt layer, he says, we put a last layer called rolling layer, made of fine stone, that is, sand that is also bagged in asphalt.
As this is the layer in contact with the wheels of the vehicles, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt layer and provide adhesion in the street.
Since the part of the pavement that receives and distributes the efforts, the rolling layer also requires that it has an adequate thickness and the material of which it is made must be cared.
Climate, particularly moisture and temperature variations, are also a very important factor to consider, particularly water, as these significantly affect the efficiency of the asphalt layer.
When the soil wets, the water spreads inside the layer is difficult to remove this, which ramps all the layers of the pavement and thus causes cassis.
In the process of formation of a cassis, he says, the first that breaks is the rolling film and only later affects the asphalt layer, but the damage does not occur immediately, but it is a process that needs to be treated with the first signals with adequate maintenance programs.
The member of the National Research System explained that the load of vehicles is another important factor for the formation of cassette and therefore the thickness of each layer of the pavement must always be linked to the load of vehicles and ensure its satisfaction, in order to avoid frequent load of cassette formation.
Rafael Herrera has warned that there is still a lot to investigate and work on asphalt, for example, bitumine emulsions, which already exist on the market in other countries and allow for repair of cassettes easily and without having to use high temperatures.
