The Nord Stream, new door to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipe, which directly connects Western Europe to Russia by crossing the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has entered service.
It must supply gas for the equivalent of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with brightness.
More than 500 guests, of which four heads of state and government participated on the coast of the Baltic on Tuesday, between orchestra and end buffet, at the inauguration of the North Stream, the new gas pipe that directly connects Russia to Germany under sea.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch homologus Mark Rutte turned together the valve commanding the Russian gas entry into the Western European network.
With this new gas pipeline, 27.5 billion extra cubic meters of Russian gas will arrive in Western Europe every year by a 1,224 km pipeline connecting the region of Saint Petersburg to the Mecklembourg-Pomérania Land.
A second pipeline must be completed at the end of 2012, allowing to deliver a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas, the equivalent of all French consumption.
And we are already discussing the possibility of building a third on the same path.
For Gazprom, the completion of this huge farm in time and in time has airs of victory.
The project was strongly contested by Poland and the Baltic countries.
The North Stream will actually allow the delivery of gas directly to Germany, avoiding any land passage by a third country (Pologne or Ukraine).
By the way, these two countries lose a bit of power: it becomes harder for them to weigh on Russia by threatening to close access to Western European markets.
In the strongest part of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare the North Stream to a "new German-Soviet pact", in reference to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
I mean, if the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, providing its support for this Russian project, has gained greater security of its supply.
But this is at the price of a weakening of energy Europe, as the project created a breakthrough between Eastern and Western Europeans.
In five years, Russia has barely triumphed over its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, strongly gas consumers, and their decrees are in decline.
"This gas pipe is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that binds us organically," Francis Fillon confirmed by opening this gas pipe, demonstrating how large gas contracts are as political as economic.
All this explains the broad smiles displayed by the Gazprom leaders, present in number at Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this gas pipeline is also a technical exploitation.
The submarine tube is made of concrete steel to protect it from vessels' anchors.
It rests on the bottom of the sea, 200 m on average.
To build it, it had to be avoided mining fields dating from World War II.
“A hundred had to be removed or destroyed by caution,” said Jens Müller, spokeswoman of North Stream.
It was also necessary to multiply measures to protect the fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake, heavy like 242 Eiffel towers, which nothing breaks all its length: neither valve nor maintenance station.
A control platform was planned across Sweden, but the project officials rejected it while the Swedish were unwanted to see a Russian state company permanently settled across their coasts.
"In case of assault, we stop the gas passing in less than a minute," said Jens Müller.
In case of escape, the gas contained in the gas pipe is therefore exhausted into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by manufacturers who planned welding to know a escape every 100,000 years.
Monitoring of the state of the gas pipe is provided by a submarine robot, driven by a vessel, for external observation, as well as by a apparatus circulating within the gas pipe.
From the form of a cigarette, it is introduced inside the tube, width of a meter of diameter, and it is pushed by the gas.
At the arrival, after three full days of trip at a speed of 3 meters, it provides accurate information about possible metal deformations.
The gas pipe was designed to operate for 50 years without having to undergo the least repair.
The circulation of gas is simply ensured by pressure.
It is 200 bars at the start, and 100 at the arrival.
Five companies have united their forces to achieve this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
The Germans E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), along with the Dutch Gasunie and the French GDF Suez group (9% each).
These five companies have established a joint venture called Nord Stream, responsible for the construction and operation of the gas pipeline.
It has its headquarters in Zoug, Switzerland, where the tax is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then rented the company, for twenty renewable years, all of the gas transport capabilities.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, regardless of the quantity of actually transported gas," said Jens Müller.
The financing of the construction of gas pipeline was provided by shareholders to 30% and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the work should be EUR 7.4 billion for both pipelines.
For example, for GDF Suez, the investment has risen to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure to return to their expenses, since only Gazprom assumes risk.
The gas pipe emerges from the Baltic to Lubmin, on a patterned coastal plant of pins.
Valves, height 4.5 meters, form the gas output door.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specifications of the gas that arrives before it is transferred to the German gas pipes.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal receives a million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour it spends.
In full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and in 2012, 6 million.
