Why is the unemployment rate of people with disabilities so high?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for work.
The 15th week for disabled people’s employment is open today.
Despite a voluntary public policy established in 2005, the unemployment rate of people with disabilities is still twice as high as the average: 19 percent, compared to 9% for the entire population.
Encouraging?
"No, he stressed that Éric Blanchet, Director-General of Adapt, is the association that organizes the week for the employment of disabled people."
"The progress made in the past fifteen years has been significant."
“At the time, the unemployment rate was not two but three times higher.”
“There is still a lot to do.”
It must be said that for disabled people, obstacles remain many before access to employment.
They are rather older: 37% are over 50 years old (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% do not have a bachelor’s degree and the 2.3 million higher education students only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is very widespread: 53% for disabled people, compared to 38% on average.
In short, so many criteria that individually complicate the return to employment, and which “represent the node of the problem”, according to Christian Grapin, Director-General of Tremplin, an association established in 1992 to help companies recruit disabled workers.
This is for the objective brakes.
The mentalities that evolve, of course, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-Enterprise Association for the City indicated that the interviewed managers had " a low level of knowledge of disability ", with " overrepresentation of persons with rolling chairs, mental or intellectual disabilities " .
As a result, private companies with more than 20 employees are still far from achieving the employment goal of 6% of disabled workers, as set out in a 1987...
The latest known figures, dated 2008, indicate a ratio of 2.6%.
“We are now around 3%,” says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, the organization responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with this law.
The proof: the number of " taxed " establishments, as well as the amounts paid, decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59 000 to 46 000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law, which increased contributions, created a strong pressure on businesses," explains Pierre Blanc.
“But this improvement also leads to real awareness, especially in large groups.”
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared to 82% of 100 to 199 employees.
